Introduction¶

Dataset Source¶

The Heart Failure Prediction dataset used in this study was sourced from Kaggle (fedesoriano, 2021). This dataset contains health marker information for key precursors to cardiovascular disease based, and was amalgamated from the following datasets by the author:

  1. Hungarian Institute of Cardiology. Budapest: Andras Janosi, M.D.
  2. University Hospital, Zurich, Switzerland: William Steinbrunn, M.D.
  3. University Hospital, Basel, Switzerland: Matthias Pfisterer, M.D.
  4. V.A. Medical Center, Long Beach and Cleveland Clinic Foundation: Robert Detrano, M.D., Ph.D.

Target Feature¶

For this project, the target feature in this dataset will be the resting BP. That is, whether or not heart disease develops will be predicted based on the explanatory/descriptive variables.

Goals and Objectives¶

High blood pressure is an extremely prevalent, that effects a large portion of the global population. Early detection of the condition is especially important, as high blood pressure is a highly treatable condition, however, if untreated can lead to harmful diseases. A model that could aid in prediction of this condition would assist health workers in 'catching' the condition before it progresses, allowing for early treatment options.

Thus, the main objective of this project is as follows: (1) investigate whether key health markers correlate to an increase of blood pressure (2) if they are found to do so then we will ascertain which markers possess the greatest effect. Naturally this is alongside the general exploratory data analysis, cleaning and preprocessing as tasked by this Phase 1 report.

Prior to commencing, we make the assumption that the rows in our dataset are not correlated, ie that the individuals studied in the various reports that make up this dataset have no bearing on the data of each other. Whilst we believe this assumption to be a realistic one for the subject matter in question, we are not privy to the details of the participants and as such cannot know with certainty.

Data Cleaning¶

  • Changing of any UIDS
  • Removal of constant features
  • Removal of irrelevant and redundant features
  • As there are no datetime features these do not need to be removed
  • Dealing with outliers via either clamping, imputing or dropping of values
  • Removal of missing rows with missing values
  • Encoding of necessary features
  • Any necessary scaling of now converted descriptive features

As our dataset is quite clean already, minimal cleanup needed to be performed, barring the below. As requested we have left the task of clamping, scaling, outlier handling, and encoding for Phase 2.

Upon further exploration of the data, we noticed that a few rows have a cholesterol value of 0, meaning those rows have data that is valid but do not have any data for their cholesterol level.

We have decided to keep these rows in and replace the cholesterol level with the median value for this column, 237.

There was also 1 row with a resting BP of 0 and cholesterol 0, we have removed that row to maintain data accuracy.

Summary and Conclusions¶

The prediction of high blood pressure based on health markers has been the subject of science and debate for some time now, as the ramifications for the correct prediction of this issue are significant and far-reaching. From the advancement of medical technologies by specifying key problem areas, to the simpler outcome of early detection, it is obvious that this data could have a massive impact on the lives of many.

As detailed above, for the first phase of this project we undertook to clean, preprocess and visualise the acquired dataset.

Initially we began this by standardising the naming conventions of all data features, along with examining the data for unique values and ranges to ensure data validity.

Finally, we noticed certain columns and rows with null or invalid data, these values were either standardised to the mean value of the feature or dropped. As the dataset seemed to have been cleaned to some level prior to our acquisition, further cleaning was not required but is noted in the report for the sake of understanding in future.

We noticed that the data has values which may need to undergo either clamping, scaling or encoding, however it is outside the scope of this report and will be performed in Phase 2.

We then proceeded to undertake visualisation to examine trends and patterns in the data through the use of various graph types.

From the graphs above, we can see that the resting blood pressure is unimodal and does have a few outliers that will need to be dealt with. Furthermore, it can be inferred that the older people get, the higher their resting blood pressure will be. This is the same for cholesterol levels, however the trend is not as severe as resting blood pressure and could almost be considered to have no relation at all.

There is also a potential positive correlation between abnormal resting ECG catergories and blood pressure, with ST slope being a possible indicator on the blood pressure range.

Further data analysis will be required in Phase 2 to better understand the key relationships between the various features.
